595
00:42:15,680 --> 00:42:18,560
Scott: Not anywhere in the United States is there a modern train.

596
00:42:18,600 --> 00:42:23,720
Rym: If there was a bullet train in New York, I could get to, we could get, like, upstate faster than flying.

597
00:42:24,840 --> 00:42:24,941
Scott: Yep.

598
00:42:25,363 --> 00:42:27,376
Scott: I guess bullet train is an unfortunate name, but...

599
00:42:27,980 --> 00:42:28,162
Rym: Nah.

600
00:42:28,892 --> 00:42:29,500
Scott: Considering.

601
00:42:29,620 --> 00:42:32,445
Scott: Yeah, just a modern train, right?

602
00:42:32,585 --> 00:42:35,811
Scott: I still haven't ridden one, even after, you know, this much of my life is over.

603
00:42:35,831 --> 00:42:40,700
Scott: I still have not ridden on a modern train, because I haven't gone to any of the countries that have them.

604
00:42:40,940 --> 00:42:41,180
Rym: Yep.

605
00:42:41,360 --> 00:43:06,199
Rym: But I think what's most important about trains is, aside from, you know, all the energy efficiency and the infrastructure inertia and everything, it's that I don't have that much time to live, and before I lived in a place where I didn't have to drive, I spent a lot of time piloting a car, and you can only do so much that is not driving.

606
00:43:06,560 --> 00:43:07,220
Rym: when you're driving.

607
00:43:07,280 --> 00:43:15,837
Rym: You can listen to a podcast, listen to some music, maybe have a not super intense conversation with someone, and that's about it.

608
00:43:15,917 --> 00:43:17,380
Rym: You're basically wasting that time.

609
00:43:18,280 --> 00:43:18,380
Scott: Yep.

610
00:43:18,480 --> 00:43:26,320
Scott: It's like, if you drive somewhere for an hour, right, you get an hour older, that's almost the same as just dying an hour sooner.

611
00:43:26,660 --> 00:43:36,371
Rym: I would rather take a train somewhere that takes three hours than drive somewhere in an hour, because sure, that three hours, I am limited to what I can do, but you know what?

612
00:43:36,752 --> 00:43:42,098
Rym: I'm sitting on a train with my laptop and my Switch and my phone and some snacks.

613
00:43:42,478 --> 00:43:44,140
Rym: That's what the fuck I'm doing at home anyway.

614
00:43:45,161 --> 00:43:55,019
Scott: Yeah, and it's, you know, unlike, you know, people can attempt on an airplane to join the Mile High Club, but on a train, right, you can get on a, you know, proper trains.

615
00:43:55,640 --> 00:43:56,788
Rym: I'm in the train club.

616
00:43:56,908 --> 00:43:58,519
Rym: I am absolutely in the train club.

617
00:43:59,300 --> 00:44:01,050
Scott: Yeah, proper trains have cabins.

618
00:44:01,191 --> 00:44:02,880
Scott: You can get it on on a train.

619
00:44:03,100 --> 00:44:04,064
Scott: I have done that.

620
00:44:04,084 --> 00:44:07,540
Rym: Full disclosure, that has happened on multiple occasions.

621
00:44:08,261 --> 00:44:09,820
Scott: I'm just saying, you can do it, right?

622
00:44:10,100 --> 00:44:10,758
Scott: You can do it on Amtrak.

623
00:44:11,342 --> 00:44:14,900
Scott: It's okay to do it, unlike on an airplane where you can get caught and get in trouble.

624
00:44:14,980 --> 00:44:18,600
Rym: So get this, you know how Emily and I usually, if we go visit her family out in LeRoy.

625
00:44:18,702 --> 00:44:19,459
Scott: If not expected.

626
00:44:20,200 --> 00:44:25,620
Rym: So we could fly to LeRoy, which is near Buffalo, like way upstate by RIT.

627
00:44:26,340 --> 00:44:39,920
Rym: Flying, it's about an hour flight, actually it's like a 45 minute flight, plus an hour to get to the airport, plus an hour of security bullshit and waiting, plus getting from the airport in a car that I have to rent all the way over.

628
00:44:40,501 --> 00:44:54,560
Rym: Or I can take, we can take like a six and a half hour Amtrak in a private car with two beds and internet and holes and a private toilet or a giant room with a shower and stuff in it.

629
00:44:55,020 --> 00:45:06,740
Rym: And those rooms cost, the difference between a regular economy ticket on Amtrak and an economy ticket plus being in that room is less than the cost of a flight.

630
00:45:08,223 --> 00:45:09,819
Scott: Yeah, depends where you're going, but yeah.

631
00:45:10,080 --> 00:45:14,827
Rym: Well, when you're going, those trains, those sleeper cars are only on a few lines.

632
00:45:14,907 --> 00:45:16,389
Rym: So you know what they're not on?

633
00:45:16,729 --> 00:45:23,960
Rym: The lines that go from here to like DC, because if there were sleeper cars to DC, I would go to mag vest in a sleeper car.

634
00:45:24,801 --> 00:45:25,041
Scott: Sure.

635
00:45:25,402 --> 00:45:32,040
Scott: But I mean, there's also trains out there that are like, there's a train out in California that has special cars with glass sides.

636
00:45:32,602 --> 00:45:38,439
Rym: I rode in one of those when way back we went to PAX for, uh, you know, PAX and then Scott left.

637
00:45:39,460 --> 00:45:51,217
Scott: And I sit in this train and you look out the window and it's like the train ride itself becomes, you know, a special, you know, like it's now, you know, a special thing in and of itself.

638
00:45:51,297 --> 00:45:53,660
Scott: It's not just a means of getting from here to there.

639
00:45:54,801 --> 00:46:01,900
Scott: It's almost more like a, it's almost approaching like a cruise where it's like, yeah, it's getting you here to there, but it's also itself a destination.

640
00:46:01,980 --> 00:46:02,642
Rym: It's amazing.

641
00:46:02,682 --> 00:46:09,178
Rym: The seats are sideways and you're facing giant panoramic windows and usually there's little lookout towers that you can climb up into.

642
00:46:10,480 --> 00:46:15,900
Scott: And, but it's like their train tracks specifically go past beautiful scenic vistas that you're looking at.

643
00:46:16,080 --> 00:46:18,868
Rym: I only rode those once, but way back and we were at that PAX West.

644
00:46:18,928 --> 00:46:23,360
Rym: after you went home, I had a lecturing gig at, uh, I think Kai Fu in Portland.

645
00:46:23,861 --> 00:46:31,960
Rym: So they paid for me to take a fancy Amtrak to Portland from Seattle and I enjoyed that Vista and it was fantastic and I'd like to do it again someday.

646
00:46:32,381 --> 00:46:33,985
Scott: Even if you don't have the Vista, right?

647
00:46:34,045 --> 00:46:40,380
Scott: It's like, you know, you think about like old style, old school train, like, you know, murder on the Orient Express, right?

648
00:46:40,520 --> 00:46:43,080
Scott: It's like, it's like a moving dinner party.

649
00:46:45,521 --> 00:46:59,720
Rym: I was, I bought a ticket to take the Orient Express to Istanbul many, many years ago, uh, because I was doing some travel for work and I was going all around Europe and all this stuff and I looked and I was like, you know what?

650
00:47:00,500 --> 00:47:03,407
Rym: It's actually not really much more expensive than flying.

651
00:47:03,888 --> 00:47:08,860
Rym: I'll just use some vacation days and I was going to take the Orient Express to Istanbul.

652
00:47:08,902 --> 00:47:09,298
Scott: But you didn't.

653
00:47:09,860 --> 00:47:12,624
Rym: I didn't because the coup attempt happened in Turkey.

654
00:47:12,644 --> 00:47:17,932
Rym: Uh, it failed and I canceled my trip and I haven't been to Turkey since.

655
00:47:18,232 --> 00:47:20,916
Rym: and because I wasn't going to Turkey, I had to curtail that whole trip.

656
00:47:20,957 --> 00:47:22,899
Rym: So I just went to Germany and I canceled everything else.

657
00:47:24,201 --> 00:47:25,965
Rym: And then I never had an excuse to go back.

658
00:47:26,005 --> 00:47:30,455
Rym: and then there's COVID and the Orient Express goes through some troubled lands these days.

659
00:47:30,535 --> 00:47:32,540
Rym: So it's a different situation than it was back then.

660
00:47:33,462 --> 00:47:40,080
Scott: So I guess the last thing train-wise, right, is that there's this huge, you know, nerdery around trains.

661
00:47:40,160 --> 00:47:45,720
Rym: Oh, as a kid, I was obsessed with model railroads and I was also obsessed with actual trains.

662
00:47:46,360 --> 00:47:47,863
Scott: It's true for cars too, right?

663
00:47:47,883 --> 00:47:51,712
Scott: You got your hot wheels and you got your, you know, hot rods and car nerds, right?

664
00:47:51,732 --> 00:47:55,380
Scott: You got your airplane nerds doing flight simulator and all that, right?

665
00:47:55,480 --> 00:48:00,989
Scott: But train nerds, it's like these nerds are every kind of transportation, boat nerds too.

666
00:48:01,289 --> 00:48:07,820
Scott: But the train nerds somehow seem different and apart from the other transportation nerds.

667
00:48:07,860 --> 00:48:08,116
Rym: Oh yeah.

668
00:48:08,700 --> 00:48:08,963
Scott: Right?

669
00:48:09,146 --> 00:48:10,300
Scott: In some kind of way.

670
00:48:10,600 --> 00:48:10,681
Scott: The

671
00:48:10,702 --> 00:48:11,618
Rym: train nerds, what I find

672
00:48:11,679 --> 00:48:24,300
Scott: is- I can't, it's like, it's hard to put my finger on exactly what it is because it's like, it's like there's people who make model airplanes, people who do model trains, people who go to the airport and watch planes take off, people who go to the train station and watch trains come and go, right?

673
00:48:24,320 --> 00:48:31,400
Scott: It's like everything, there's no particular thing that you can say train nerds are doing that other forms of transportation nerds are not doing.

674
00:48:31,420 --> 00:48:35,920
Rym: But yeah, if you add them all up, the train nerds stand apart and we all know this.

675
00:48:36,541 --> 00:48:47,720
Scott: There's some sort of aesthetic and attitude and, you know, behavior of the train nerds that is different from the other transportation nerds.

676
00:48:47,820 --> 00:48:56,860
Rym: One thing I noticed just as a kid because I was really into trains and one friend of the family, like one of the dads, he was one of those come into my basement train dads.

677
00:48:57,383 --> 00:48:59,960
Scott: And he had the whole- I knew quite a few of those, two or three of them.

678
00:49:00,080 --> 00:49:02,580
Rym: The whole basement set up and I was obsessed with it.

679
00:49:02,620 --> 00:49:06,340
Scott: If I had a basement, there's a non-zero chance I would be that.

680
00:49:06,360 --> 00:49:09,159
Rym: Non-zero, there is a one chance that I would have that.

681
00:49:09,883 --> 00:49:10,439
Scott: Oh, wow, okay.

682
00:49:10,660 --> 00:49:16,120
Rym: Because I had model, as a kid, I had HO gauge and I had a bunch of different gauge model railroads.

683
00:49:16,460 --> 00:49:20,040
Scott: The tiny ones- And an oval on a flat board and it was kind of sad.

684
00:49:20,360 --> 00:49:21,680
Rym: Oh, I had switching mechanisms and everything.

685
00:49:21,901 --> 00:49:24,300
Rym: I had all these hardcover books on like train nonsense.

686
00:49:24,920 --> 00:49:34,820
Rym: But one thing I like, one of the aspects of the train nerds that seems hyper specific focus is there's this extreme attention to detail that I don't see in those other hobbies.

687
00:49:35,420 --> 00:49:45,440
Rym: Like extreme attention to detail in terms of period accuracy and operational and logistical accuracy.

688
00:49:45,500 --> 00:50:05,920
Rym: Case in point, every train nerd, the highlight of their set up, if they're a basement train nerd with the basement set up, in my experience, I don't know if someone might correct me and they have a different experience, is the complicated switching mechanisms and showing off all the ways they can route the trains and simulate the real routing that happens in the real world.

689
00:50:07,541 --> 00:50:22,440
Rym: Like activating and deactivating the switching and the signaling is something like most of the flight nerds I know don't hyper, like the flight sim people, they don't necessarily simulate the full ground control, air traffic control experience.

690
00:50:22,540 --> 00:50:25,920
Rym: They mostly simulate the operating the plane experience.

691
00:50:26,540 --> 00:50:29,620
Scott: No, there's those people who are online who are like pretending to be flight control.

692
00:50:29,820 --> 00:50:30,643
Rym: There's a subset.

693
00:50:30,763 --> 00:50:35,520
Rym: I would say that subset of airplane people are nearly identical to train people.

694
00:50:35,721 --> 00:50:42,240
Rym: I just think in train nerdery, that type of focus is the majority, where in these other communities it's the minority.

695
00:50:42,740 --> 00:50:43,418
Rym: That is a speculative guess.

696
00:50:43,500 --> 00:50:55,720
Scott: Or maybe it could be because trains in the United States have fallen so far that the train nerds have, by and large, are more overlapping with historical things.

697
00:50:55,900 --> 00:51:02,818
Scott: And even though there are, there are people who do the classic cars, there are people who do the old planes at the air show, right?

698
00:51:03,881 --> 00:51:18,840
Scott: But I think maybe it could be that there's a great overlap of the train nerds with history, you know, as a percentage of train, a percentage of overall train nerds being historic train nerds, where I think a lot of car nerds are like modern car nerds.

699
00:51:18,960 --> 00:51:30,880
Rym: But also you can make physical working model railroads with accurate switching and simulate a lot, a terrifying percentage of real world train stuff.

700
00:51:31,342 --> 00:51:35,040
Rym: Can't really do that with cars or planes in your basement.

701
00:51:35,920 --> 00:51:46,379
Scott: I think the other thing is that the train nerds also have an element of real world preservation, at least in the United States, of geographic places.

702
00:51:47,942 --> 00:51:53,740
Scott: There might be an airfield here or there that someone is, you know, preserving and turning into a museum.

703
00:51:54,240 --> 00:51:59,280
Scott: There might, you know, cars, like there aren't really planes, maybe an old racetrack or something here or there.

704
00:51:59,400 --> 00:52:07,400
Rym: But go to any town that has a defunct railroad, there is a society of like three guys with beards who are dedicated to restoring it.

705
00:52:07,920 --> 00:52:17,900
Scott: There are old stations and train tracks all over the place that have little foundations that are turning them into museums and preserving them and checking them out.

706
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:24,340
Rym: In Beacon, where we lived, there was, there used to be a hotel and a ski resort at the top of the mountain in Beacon, like in town.

707
00:52:24,921 --> 00:52:25,983
Rym: And we go hike up there a lot.

708
00:52:26,364 --> 00:52:33,560
Rym: There was also a railroad, an inclined railroad that went from Beacon, like downtown, up the mountain to this hotel.

709
00:52:34,441 --> 00:52:41,019
Rym: And it was dilapidated, it went out of service in like the 50s and then some vandals burned it down, like what was left in the 70s.

710
00:52:42,120 --> 00:52:49,540
Rym: While we were living there, there was a very vocal society of I'm pretty sure exactly seven men, all of whom had white beards.

711
00:52:50,001 --> 00:52:57,159
Rym: And they were desperately, constantly, aggressively trying to raise money to rebuild that inclined railroad and then run it.

712
00:52:58,080 --> 00:53:10,600
Scott: Right, because even though this collapse happened, the collapse was within the lifetimes of not slightly before our lifetime, but well within the lifetimes of many, many people who are still alive, right?

713
00:53:11,241 --> 00:53:13,045
Scott: And, you know, still of sound mind.

714
00:53:13,546 --> 00:53:19,480
Scott: And they're like, hey, I remember a time where there was all this awesome shit and all that shit is gone, right?

715
00:53:19,700 --> 00:53:28,117
Rym: The metro north train that used to go from Beacon across into Connecticut was still active, while many people who are alive today, like they're still alive.

716
00:53:28,157 --> 00:53:29,640
Rym: Like that was active in living memory.

717
00:53:30,180 --> 00:53:35,538
Scott: Right, I mean, when you think about like us, like I guess, you know, in terms of our memory of the heyday would be like the 90s, right?

718
00:53:36,100 --> 00:53:42,620
Scott: And it's like, but none of us are out there like, you know, bring back malls with all this garbage in them, right?

719
00:53:42,780 --> 00:53:43,221
Scott: But it's like.

720
00:53:43,241 --> 00:53:50,340
Scott: we have, you know, memories of that, of like a time where there were like these things that existed that were built up and awesome that then went away.

721
00:53:50,841 --> 00:53:57,280
Scott: But if the things that we remember for the 90s being built up and awesome that went away were actually like useful things.

722
00:53:58,841 --> 00:54:07,399
Scott: Right, like I would be, you know, if it wasn't shopping malls, I would be like, hey, you know, earlier in my life, shit was cool and that shit is all gone.

723
00:54:07,419 --> 00:54:07,680
Scott: What the fuck?

724
00:54:07,680 --> 00:54:08,241
Rym: You know what?

725
00:54:08,281 --> 00:54:08,782
Rym: Here's something.

726
00:54:08,822 --> 00:54:10,445
Rym: There's one thing from our childhood, arcades.

727
00:54:10,765 --> 00:54:19,160
Rym: We are some of the, we're literally some of the youngest people who experienced an era where there were multiple arcades in every town.

728
00:54:20,080 --> 00:54:26,020
Scott: Yeah, but the problem is, is like we sort of recognize that like bringing back arcades isn't really, you know, great.

729
00:54:26,862 --> 00:54:36,200
Scott: It's not really worth trying to bring back and you couldn't bring it back in the way it was and just plenty of people are preserving the machines and we can set them up anywhere.

730
00:54:36,660 --> 00:54:37,439
Scott: And like, that's fine.

731
00:54:37,860 --> 00:54:40,832
Rym: But similarly, we don't want to bring back the trains from the 70s.

732
00:54:40,892 --> 00:54:42,157
Rym: We want to make trains in 2022s.

733
00:54:43,240 --> 00:54:54,360
Rym: I don't want to bring back the exact details of a 1989 arcade, but there's aspects of what happened in arcades and what those structures were that I want to reinvent and bring back.

734
00:54:54,700 --> 00:54:55,221
Rym: What stops?

735
00:54:55,261 --> 00:55:08,820
Rym: that is primarily, actually, I think the fact that the people who want those new experiences mostly live in cities and because of capitalism, it is literally impossible to pay the rent on the space you would need to have an arcade.

736
00:55:09,380 --> 00:55:11,619
Scott: Arcade doesn't really make economic sense in most places.

737
00:55:11,760 --> 00:55:11,901
Scott: Nope.

738
00:55:12,242 --> 00:55:16,520
Scott: But if somehow you could have an arcade in Japan, you can see the arcades are closing.

739
00:55:16,720 --> 00:55:20,420
Rym: If you could somehow have arcades even before the pandemic, they would be packed.

740
00:55:20,721 --> 00:55:26,220
Rym: Look at Barcade, which kind of sucks because it's so loud and so crowded.

741
00:55:26,460 --> 00:55:27,620
Scott: They make all their money from booze.

742
00:55:28,782 --> 00:55:31,160
Scott: It's like, I don't make the money from the arcade games.

743
00:55:31,420 --> 00:55:33,840
Rym: Also, people are packed for deep waiting in line to play.

744
00:55:33,900 --> 00:55:34,999
Rym: They're desperate to play the games.

745
00:55:35,101 --> 00:55:35,980
Rym: It's so packed.

746
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:37,020
Rym: You're trying to like shove your way.

747
00:55:37,240 --> 00:55:38,220
Scott: They're just they're just drunk.

748
00:55:38,321 --> 00:55:40,999
Scott: So they don't realize how crappy it is to play a lot of those games.

749
00:55:42,303 --> 00:55:43,159
Rym: That's me at Magfest.

750
00:55:44,262 --> 00:55:47,100
Scott: Or, you know, the games are there for the social aspect, right?

751
00:55:47,883 --> 00:55:51,698
Rym: I just I really miss the social aspect of just playing competitive games with strangers in person.

752
00:55:52,626 --> 00:55:53,219
Scott: Yeah, me too.

753
00:55:53,360 --> 00:55:59,300
Scott: But I also miss, you know, you know, I guess I don't miss riding a train.

754
00:55:59,440 --> 00:56:00,178
Scott: I just rode one.

755
00:56:00,520 --> 00:56:01,871
Rym: But here I miss the Internet.

756
00:56:01,891 --> 00:56:02,839
Rym: before spam existed.

757
00:56:04,203 --> 00:56:04,810
Rym: That used to exist.

758
00:56:05,960 --> 00:56:06,840
Scott: So there were no such thing.

759
00:56:07,783 --> 00:56:09,819
Scott: At the end of the day, it was spam way before we got on there.

760
00:56:10,940 --> 00:56:11,620
Rym: Well, depends.

761
00:56:11,900 --> 00:56:13,700
Rym: So early email, I never got spam.

762
00:56:14,260 --> 00:56:15,080
Rym: I didn't have any spam filters.

763
00:56:15,080 --> 00:56:16,339
Scott: I got spam on AOL right away.

764
00:56:16,501 --> 00:56:18,000
Rym: I didn't use AOL because I wasn't stupid.

765
00:56:19,703 --> 00:56:21,240
Scott: Not like I was choosing the Internet service.

766
00:56:21,521 --> 00:56:22,880
Scott: I mean, I got off AOL pretty quickly.

767
00:56:23,762 --> 00:56:28,920
Rym: So I used burner AOL accounts with free trials to do shady shit.

768
00:56:29,220 --> 00:56:32,860
Rym: But I never used AOL on purpose, for real, for anything other than shady shit.

769
00:56:33,381 --> 00:56:36,496
Scott: That's what my family was using until I got my own computer in like '98, '99.

770
00:56:37,460 --> 00:56:39,360
Scott: Then I got my own service from the phone company.

771
00:56:39,480 --> 00:56:40,640
Scott: But even that, I got spam.

772
00:56:40,880 --> 00:56:41,939
Scott: I got to RIT, got spam.

773
00:56:42,440 --> 00:56:44,380
Rym: I remember RIT, I got my first spam email.

774
00:56:44,982 --> 00:56:49,520
Rym: It wasn't until RIT because I reported it to RIT's IT department.

775
00:56:50,400 --> 00:56:56,176
Rym: I forwarded it to abuse@rit.edu and I was like, "What the fuck is this email that came to

776
00:56:56,337 --> 00:56:56,397
Rym: me?".

777
00:56:58,062 --> 00:57:01,939
Scott: I had spam pre-RIT from non-AOL.

778
00:57:03,401 --> 00:57:15,100
Scott: Anyway, trains are awesome and even in places that do trains right, at least there are some such places in the world, it's really like train is the way to go for a lot of things.

779
00:57:15,360 --> 00:57:16,175
Scott: There's not enough train.

780
00:57:19,384 --> 00:57:23,819
